x;">Years ago, a mentor of mine took the time to extemporize about the theo=
ry of
<em>punctuated equilibrium</em>, the concept in evolutionary biology (and s=
ince applied to politics and economics) that progress <em>rarely</em> occur=
s <em>gradually</em>, as we expect, or hope, but rather in cacophonous fits=
 and starts.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Indeed, industries don=E2=80=99t rea=
lly evolve in a piecemeal manner. Instead, there=E2=80=99s an awakening or =
disruptive technology=E2=80=94the printing press, the Renaissance, the cott=
on
gin, Ford=E2=80=99s assembly line, the iPhone, <strong>Obama</strong>, <str=
ong>Trump</strong>, ChatGPT=E2=80=94that catapults the culture forward, ine=
vitably causing a series of reverberations. As <strong>Shakespeare</strong>=
 knew well, there=E2=80=99s almost always an inciting event that provokes t=
he drama=E2=80=94or the markets=E2=80=94into action. That=E2=80=99s a truth=
 we hold to be self-evident, and one of the many reasons we=E2=80=99ve deri=
ved our name from the bard. (For those just tuning in, Puck is named after =
the mirthful narrating fairy in
<em>A Midsummer Night=E2=80=99s Dream</em>.) Anyway, without getting unnece=
ssarily philosophical, the conversation crossed my mind amid a week replete=
 with so many gyrations, oscillations, and conflagrations, from Silicon Val=
ley to Washington, D.C.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In her extraordinary debut at P=
